";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1389468652;}i:1;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:57:"Storing monetary amounts in db? Use decimals, not floats!";s:4:"link";s:77:"http://pixeljets.com/blog/storing-monetary-amounts-db-use-decimals-not-floats";s:11:"description";s:711:"<p>Lot&#8217;s of people will be surprised (or shocked, when it happens in production) when they see that mysql can work like&nbsp;this:</p>
<p>Query:</p>
<blockquote><p>SELECT transaction_id, amount FROM transactions WHERE amount<b>&gt;</b>20.5</p></blockquote>
<p>Response:</p>
<blockquote><p>123|20.5</p></blockquote>
<p>Query:</p>
<blockquote><p>SELECT transaction_id, amount FROM transactions  WHERE amount<b>=</b>20.5</p></blockquote>
<p>Response:</p>
<blockquote><p><i>No&nbsp;rows</i></p></blockquote>
<p>So, 20.5 is really greater than 20.5 in sql database.&nbsp;Sometimes.</p>
